         <abstract>
            <p>The popularity of the high-return performance cult of the mid-sixties is receding; some investors, no longer as optimistic for common stock returns as they once were, are devoting an increasing portion of their portfolios to debt securities. There are obvious risks for debt investment if inflation rates turn up again. On the other hand, it is not clear which stocks, if any, will then perform well. In the new environment, performance is likely to mean management of risk, rather than rate of return, with emphasis on a balanced investment strategy utilizing a wide range of investment vehicles.</p>
